            <outline text="Security Solutions (Controls)">
                <outline text="Analyse">
                    <outline text="Random Secret Sharing (RSS) #CI7160 #workshop ">
                        <outline text="Prerequisites." colorLabel="3">
                            <outline text="An understanding of advanced secret sharing techniques, including the Random Secret Sharing (RSS) protocol. "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Aim." colorLabel="3">
                            <outline text="To illustrate the Random Secret Sharing (RSS) protocol. "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Covered Learning Outcomes.">
                            <outline text="CI7160-LO2, CI7160-LO5 #los "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Description." colorLabel="3">
                            <outline text="Setup." colorLabel="4">
<outline text="The class is divided into $$n$$ groups, recommended group number $$n$$ is between 3 and 4. Each group requires a unique index $$i$$."/>
<outline text="Each group receives $$n$$ record cards of same colour."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Instructions." colorLabel="4">
<outline text="You will simulate the RSS protocol. Revised the slide and familiarise yourself with its content. You will simulate the exchange of messages by physically passing on record cards."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Activity.  " colorLabel="4">
<outline text="0. Write down your share on a separate piece of paper."/>
<outline text="1. On each record card, note your group (player) ID at the top, the recipient (other players) ID at the bottom and the corresponding share value in the middle. You may use generic mathematical notation, indicating the evaluation of your share polynomial."/>
<outline text="2. Send the various shares to their recipients, by passing on record cards."/>
<outline text="3. Write down the final share, by adding up all the received shares and your own private share."/>
<outline text="4. Are you now able to justify why everyone as a secret share of a random secret, which is not known to anyone at this stage?"/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Wrap-Up." colorLabel="3">
                            <outline text="Can you think of an application of this protocol?"/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Configure">
                    <outline text="[PKI Certificates](https://kingstonuniversity-my.sharepoint.com/:b:/g/personal/ku32104_kingston_ac_uk/EeX_ZjTKCOFLoE5G3x1Ir04B5Z_jwzWVSrwQhbfVwF77Rg?e=TlafXq) #CI7110 #workshop "/>
                    <outline text="Securing The Apache Webserver #CI7100 #CI7160 #workshop #todo">
                        <outline text="Scenario.">
                            <outline text="Alice works for an organisation and is in charge of securely configuring and maintaining the company's web server. Today, she is working on a fresh installation of the system and needs to download Apache if necessary, and use suitable security tools in order to create a self-signed certificate for installation with Apache. #level1 "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Solution.">
                            <outline text="She is based on a Linux environment, and has decided to proceed along the following six steps:">
<outline text="Step 1: Enable Apache on the system, if necessary.  ">
    <outline text="She might not need to install Apache. One can verify the existence or successful installation of Apache using a web browser. "/>
    <outline text="Type `localhost` into your browser address bar. You need to be able to see a generic test home page. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Step 2: If Apache is not present, she needs to install Apache.  ">
    <outline text="How to install and start in Ubuntu (Linux):">
        <outline text="The following steps are required to install the Apache web server: typ `sudo apt-get install apache2` command on the console then press enter."/>
        <outline text="Type sudo `/etc/init.d/apache2 start` or `sudo service apache2 start` to start apache."/>
        <outline text="`ps -aux | grep apache` "/>
        <outline text="After apache installation, it is required to verify if it is installed or not. To verify, type aptitude show apache2 command on the terminal. This displays the details of the apache package stating its status as shown in figure 15 below.">
            <outline text="Fig. 15: Apache installation details."/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="After installation, the next step is to enable ssl. To do this type `sudo a2enmod ssl`. This is shown in figure 16 below.">
            <outline text="Fig. 16: Enable SSL"/>
        </outline>
    </outline>
    <outline text="How to install and start in CentOS (Linux):">
        <outline text="sudo yum install httpd #linux "/>
        <outline text="systemctl start httpd #linux "/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="She can now test that Apache is running as in Step 1."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Step 3: Enable the Apache ssl module, if necessary.  ">
    <outline text="To do this, she types `sudo a2enmod ssl` on the command line. Then she can type `sudo service apache2 restart` to restart Apache. "/>
    <outline text="The ssl module can be disabled using the `sudo a2dismod ssl` command, if not required."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Step 4: Create a self-signed certificate, based on using a suitable tool.   ">
    <outline text="(a) Generate a public/private key pair with the `openssl` tool. ">
        <outline text="This requires further terminal commands, such as">
            <outline text="`openssl genrsa -out key.pem 2048`"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="You might have to enter a passphrase for your key and verify. You can use `ls` to show the created key files, and `more` or `less` to show their content."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="(b) Create a CSR (Certificate Signing Request).">
        <outline text="This requires the terminal command">
            <outline text="`openssl req -new -key key.pem -sha256 -out server.csr`"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Enter your chosen passphrase when prompted, and the X.509 attributes of the certificate such as your server's host/website name."/>
        <outline text="The CSR in the file `server.csr` is generated."/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="(c) Generate a self-signed certificate by self-signing the CSR.">
        <outline text="You will issue the following terminal command:">
            <outline text="`openssl x509 -req -days 365 -in server.csr -signkey key.pem -out server.crt`"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="Enter your chosen passphrase when prompted. The certificate gets generated in `server.crt`."/>
    </outline>
</outline>
<outline text="Step 5: Configure SSL on Apache accordingly.  ">
    <outline text="The private key and the certificate need to be copied to two locations on the system file space, referred to as `/path/to/your_private.key` and `/path/to/your_domain_name.crt`. They could be in your home directory, or in `/var/www`. "/>
    <outline text="Edit the Apache configuration file by typing `sudo nano /etc/apache2/apache.conf` (or by using any other text editor) and then adding references to these locations. This is done by adding these lines to the configuation file:">
        <outline text="`&lt;VirtualHost *:443&gt;`">
            <outline text="`ServerName your_server`"/>
            <outline text="`SSLEngine on`"/>
            <outline text="`SSLCertificateFile /path/to/your_domain_name.crt`"/>
            <outline text="`SSLCertificateKeyFile /path/to/your_private.key`"/>
        </outline>
        <outline text="`&lt;/VirtualHost&gt;`"/>
    </outline>
    <outline text="Then restart Apache, for the changes to take effect. "/>
</outline>
<outline text="Step 6: Verify the secure connection.  ">
    <outline text="Open a web browser on your local machine, then type `https://localhost` into the URL bar. The same page confirming that the Apache webserver was installed should be displayed. There may be a warning about an untrusted certificate."/>
</outline>
